# The Rising of the House's Sun

A stone from Zaragoza.  
Frio. Duro.  
A Saint pressed into it —  
permanent as faith,  
older than the all whose feet walk upon it.  

The Pyrenees receive the morning  
before the city does.  
The sun does not rise over them —  
it rises beside them,  
and they take the light first,  
the way fathers do.  

Beneath the Saint, older hands.  
The Celts came through those same mountains —  
their words pressed into bronze  
beside this same river,  
this same soil.  

They crossed  
and were never quite  
from anywhere again.  

He came the same way,  
through mountains,  
with everything he was  
held loosely —  

not stone, not yet.  
Still clay.  
Still taking the shape  
of wherever the light falls.  

No root.  
No stone.  

Taking the shape of the tide,  
the direction of then.  

He was free the way water is free —  
formless.  

He planted himself  
On Weala lande to settanne  
and grew,  
and still grows,  

one foot in the Ebro,  
one in the rain.  

And in Zaragoza, a man.  
The sun already high  
by the time he rose.  

He moved the way stone moves —  
slowly, solidly,  
knowing where it stands.  

He would not be shifted.  
Not by weather.  
Not by argument.  
Not by the particular brightness  
of a son who thought  
light was enough  
to move anything.  

He was the house.  
The sun did not yet understand  
what it means  
to be made of something  
that will not bend.  

The sun was still rising  
when the news came  
across the water.  

Brief.  
Certain.  
The way stone falls.  

He had not finished  
learning the language  
of his father's silences.  

Learning the direction of now.
